        It's calculated by their official positional changes week on week. 75pts for #1, 74 for #2 down to 1pt for #75. With streaming, ACR and the 3-single rule, comparing this method to the official sales chart shows the impact of such artificial chart manipulation. Much more pronounced than in the physical era when such rules were not in place.

        It's also a method I used to see how big or small a hit is, even when full sales data is not published or difficult to obtain. OCC (and earlier publications like Guinness Hit Singles) used to count number of weeks as a scale of chart impact where a #1 is equal to a #75 and everything in between. This makes it a bit more accurate, but also interesting to compare to the sales chart which ones gained a lot of "chart impact" with fewer sales by charting for a long time lower down the chart, and those that has a lot of sales in a short period (e.g. a big-selling #1).

        It highlights the #1s that were hyped and those that more genuine long-term favourites with the public, if they didn't have an instant impact.
